“An EC2-based application suddenly becomes unreachable, but the instance is still running. CPU looks normal. What do you do?”

Most candidates jumped straight to restart the instance.
That answer ends interviews.

Here’s how a real DevOps engineer thinks.

𝐒𝐭𝐞𝐩 𝟏: 𝐃𝐨𝐧’𝐭 𝐭𝐫𝐮𝐬𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐞 “𝐫𝐮𝐧𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠” 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞
An EC2 instance being running doesn’t mean the app is healthy.
 First check:
• System Status Check
• Instance Status Check
If Instance Status Check fails, the OS or network stack is the issue — not AWS hardware.

𝐒𝐭𝐞𝐩 𝟐: 𝐕𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐝𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐧𝐞𝐭𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐜𝐡𝐚𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐭𝐲
Before touching the server:
• Security Group inbound rules
• NACL rules
• Route table association
• Public IP or Elastic IP attached
In many real outages, a recent SG change is the real culprit.

𝐒𝐭𝐞𝐩 𝟑: 𝐒𝐒𝐇 𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤𝐬, 𝐚𝐩𝐩 𝐝𝐨𝐞𝐬𝐧’𝐭
If SSH is accessible but the app isn’t:
• Check disk usage (df -h)
• Check memory (free -m)
• Check process health (systemctl status, ps, logs)
In this case, logs showed:
• Disk was 100% full due to unchecked application logs
• App silently failed to write data

𝐒𝐭𝐞𝐩 𝟒: 𝐅𝐢𝐱 + 𝐩𝐫𝐞𝐯𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐮𝐫𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐜𝐞
Immediate fix:
• Clean logs
• Restart service
Long-term fix (this is what interviewers want):
• Enable log rotation
• Add CloudWatch disk alarms
• Create an AMI backup
• Use Auto Scaling + Load Balancer for resilience

𝐖𝐡𝐲 𝐭𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐬𝐰𝐞𝐫 𝐦𝐚𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐬
This isn’t about EC2 commands.
 It’s about thinking in systems, not servers.
That’s the difference between:
• Someone who uses AWS
• Someone who can handle a 20+ LPA DevOps role

Never rush to restart.
First understand why the system failed and how you’ll prevent it next time.
